d decline of a hegemonic America. Global Shift begins with the end of the Second World War, telling the story of a ravaged, but still dominant West, as well as the emergence of the Third World - a zone of competition and contention ultimately engulfed by the rising tide of capitalist development. Mason suggests that historic focus on the West as the centre of the global economy may soon be superseded by the rise of the East Drawing on history, comparative politics, and development studies, Global Shift traces the contours of state histories from Asia, Africa, and Latin America to create a comprehensive portrait of the current state of global politics that is breathtaking in scope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEconomic developmentzDeveloping countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358769440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587694423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587694/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles